"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">31</A>
These two retorts are recorded by Plutarch,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Demosthenes*.html#11.5
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Life of Demosthenes</I>, chap. xi p851</A>. The second obviously refers to misconduct on the part of Demades. "The sow (teaches


<A ID="p185x"></A>or contends with) Athena" was a proverbial expression; <I>cf.</I> Theocritus, <I>Idyl.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">V</SPAN>.23. As <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">sus (docet) Minervam</SPAN> the proverb was current in Latin; <I>cf.</I> Festus, p310 Müller, p408 Lindsay; Cicero,
	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/cicero/fam9.shtml#18
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Cicero\'s Epistulae<BR>ad Familiares to that letter'+Lat2+LatSearch+'Minervam</SPAN>.<BR>')"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Ad Familiares</I>, <SPAN CLASS="small">IX</SPAN>.18.3</A>;	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/cicero/fam9.shtml#18
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Cicero\'s Academica'+Lat2+LatSearch+'Minervam</SPAN>.<BR>')"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Academica</I>, <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.4.8</A>;
	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/cicero/oratore2.shtml#233
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2,WIDTH,190)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>De Oratore</I>, <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.57.233</A>.


