E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref60
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">60</A>
Homer, <I>Il.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">VII</SPAN>.358.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note61" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref61
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">61</A>
Homer, <I>Il.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">V</SPAN>.800, referring to Diomedes.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note62" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref62
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">62</A>
Scipio Africanus the younger (185‑129 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>) was the son of Lucius Aemilius Paulus.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note63" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref63
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">63</A>
	<A HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/tragicorumgraeco00naucuoft#page/312/mode/2up
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Nauck, <I>Trag. Graec. Frag.</I> p312, no. 711.
	</A>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note64" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref64
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">64</A>
No such official as <SPAN CLASS="translit_Greek">telearchos</SPAN> is mentioned elsewhere, and the word itself describes no function. On the other hand, <SPAN CLASS="translit_Greek">telmarchos</SPAN> or <SPAN CLASS="translit_Greek">telmatarchos</SPAN>, conjectured independently


<A ID="p223x"></A>by Winckelmann and van Herwerden, although not found elsewhere, gives a meaning which accords with Plutarch's description, "official of stagnant pools," or a special kind of collector of refuse and other nuisances from the streets, very like the <SPAN CLASS="translit_Greek">koprologoi</SPAN> of Athens.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note65" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref65
