Nauck, <I>Trag. Graec. Frag.</I> p918, no. 412</A>; from an unknown play.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note77" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref77
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">77</A>
Bergk, <I>Poet. Lyr. Graec.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN> p34.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note78" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref78
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">78</A>
The Thirty Tyrants at Athens were overthrown in 403 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>; Phrynichus presented the tragedy shortly after Miletus was captured by the Persians in 494 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>; Cassander


<A ID="p239x"></A>refounded Thebes in 316‑315 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>, ten years after its destruction by Alexander; the clubbing of aristocrats at Argos by the mob took place in 370 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>; Harpalus, Alexander's treasurer, brought to Athens in 329 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> funds stolen from Alexander and was supposed to have bribed many prominent Athenians, one of whom was Demosthenes.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note79" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref79
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">79</A>
<I>i.e.</I> the Romans.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note80" HREF="
