"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Life of Antony</I>, chap. lxxx</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note82" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref82
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">82</A>
This refers to the Roman custom of greeting at the front door.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note83" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref83
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">83</A>
Euripides in <I>Phoenissae</I> 524 f. represents Eteocles as saying —

<DIV ALIGN="center"><TABLE CLASS="Greek verse">
	<TR>
		<TD>
			<P>
εἴπερ γὰρ ἀδικεῖν χρή, τυραννίδος πέρι
			<P>
κάλλιστον ἀδικεῖν.
		</TD>
	</TR>
</TABLE></DIV>
<DIV ALIGN="center"><TABLE CLASS="verse">
	<TR>
		<TD>
			<P>
If wrong be ever right, for the throne's sake
			<P>
Were wrong most right. (Way's translation.)
		</TD>
	</TR>
</TABLE></DIV>

	<P CLASS="halfstart justify">
If Plutarch quotes this passage, correcting it to suit his purpose,


<A ID="p243x"></A>he simply substitutes <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">ἀγρυπνεῖν</SPAN> for <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">ἀδικεῖν</SPAN> and <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">πατρίδος</SPAN> for <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">τυραννίδος</SPAN>. And the sentiment about equality, as the basis of true friendship, seems to be an echo of 535 f. of the same play. This method of dealing with passages from the poets is not infrequently employed by Plutarch.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note84" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref84
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">84</A>
This doubtless refers to honorary <SPAN CLASS="whole">citizen</SPAN>&shy;ship, crowns, statues, and the like.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note85" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref85
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">85</A>
The citizens of most ancient states were divided into tribes or clans.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note86" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref86
