	</P></DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note92" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref92
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">92</A>
Athenian youths from eighteen to twenty years of age were called <SPAN CLASS="translit_Greek">ephebi</SPAN>. For one year they were trained chiefly in gymnastics and military drill, then for a year they served


<A ID="p249x"></A>as guards on the frontier. <I>Cf.</I> Aristotle, <I>Constitution of Athens</I>, chap. xlii.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note93" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref93
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">93</A>
Apparently a quotation from a comedy. See
	<A HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/comicorumatticor03kockuoft#page/495/mode/2up
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Kock, <I>Com. Att. Frag.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN> p495</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note94" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref94
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">94</A>
Theodorus and Polus were famous actors at Athens in the fourth century <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> See J. B. O'Connor, <I>Chapters in the


<A ID="p255x"></A>History of Actors and Acting in Ancient Greece</I>, pp100, 128. The terms <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">τραγῳδός</SPAN> and <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">κωμῳδός</SPAN> were used for actors who had been assigned to the highest rank and were privileged to bring out old plays at the festivals, and they stand in sharp contrast to the "hireling" actors, usually referred to after Demosthenes' time as "tritagonists," to whom were often given the "third-class" roles of kings; see <I>ibid.</I> chap. <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note95" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref95
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">95</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Cicero*.html#2.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><I>Life of Cicero</I>, chap. ii</A>, "Cicero placed in their midst, as a mark of honour," Perrin's translation, <I>L. C. L.</I>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note96" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref96
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">96</A>
Homer, <I>Il.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">IV</SPAN>.415.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note97" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref97
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">97</A>
Demosthenes, <SPAN CLASS="small">XXI</SPAN> (<I>Against Meidias</I>) 524. Meidias had insulted Demosthenes in public when Demosthenes was choregus, officially appointed to bear the expense of a chorus.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note98" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref98
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">98</A>
The thesmothetae were the six junior archons at Athens. Their chief duty was supervision of the courts of law.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note99" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref99
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">99</A>
The stephanephori were officials whose duties varied in different cities. At Athens they were concerned with public festivals.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note100" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref100
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">100</A>
The author of the <I>Anabasis</I>. But Plutarch may have written <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">φησὶν αὐτός</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note101" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref101
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">101</A>
Xenophon, <I>Anab.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN>.1.4.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note102" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref102
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">102</A>
The Boeotarchy was the chief office of the Boeotian confederacy. Its term was one year.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note103" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref103
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">103</A>
These measures included the freeing of Messenia from Spartan domination and the foundation of the city of Messenê.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note104" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref104
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">104</A>
	<A HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/tragicorumgraeco00naucuoft#page/918/mode/2up
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Nauck, <I>Trag. Graec. Frag.</I> p918, no. 413.
	</A>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note105" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref105
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">105</A>
Plato, <I>Republic</I>, 552<SPAN CLASS="small">C</SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="small">D</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note106" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref106
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">106</A>
In 330 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> King Agis of Sparta headed the revolt.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note107" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref107
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">107</A>
The second day of the <SPAN CLASS="translit_Greek">Anthesteria</SPAN>, a three-day festival in worship of Dionysus, held in early spring at Athens.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note108" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref108
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">108</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Phocion*.html#24.3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><I>Life of Phocion</I>, chap. xxiv</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note109" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref109
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">109</A>
<I>Cf.</I> Homer, <I>Il.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">X</SPAN>.243. He chose Odysseus.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note110" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref110
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">110</A>
This refers to Jason's seduction of Medea.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note111" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref111
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">111</A>
<I>Cf.</I> Plato, <I>Republic</I>, 609<SPAN CLASS="small">A</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note112" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref112
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">112</A>
Homer, <I>Od.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">V</SPAN>.350.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note113" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref113
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">113</A>
Plato, <I>Republic</I>, 416<SPAN CLASS="small">E</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note114" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref114
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">114</A>
Two famous statues. The doryphorus (spear-bearer) was by Polycleitus.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note115" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref115
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">115</A>
The prizes at the Olympic, Pythian, Isthmian, and Nemean games were crowns of wild olive, laurel, pine, and parsley respectively.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note116" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref116
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">116</A>
Epimenides of Crete was called in by the Athenians, apparently not far from 500 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>, to purify the city of a pestilence.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note117" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref117
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">117</A>
Mullach, <I>Frag. Phil. Graec.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN> p3, 112.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note118" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref118
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">118</A>
Quoted with slightly different wording by Plutarch, <I>Moralia</I>, 1113<SPAN CLASS="small">B</SPAN><!--</A>PLUTARCH:ADV COLOTEN-->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note119" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref119
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">119</A>
Mullach, <I>Frag. Phil. Graec.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN> p355.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note120" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref120
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">120</A>
Homer, <I>Il.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">XIX</SPAN>.404 ff.; <A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Aelian/de_Natura_Animalium/6*.html#25
	"TARGET="Aelian_L"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Aelian,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Aelian, <I>De Natura Animal.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">VI</SPAN>.25</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note121" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref121
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">121</A>
Demosthenes, <SPAN CLASS="small">VI</SPAN> (second <I>Philippic</I>) 24.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note122" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref122
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">122</A>
	<A HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/tragicorumgraeco00naucuoft#page/919/mode/2up
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Nauck, <I>Trag. Graec. Frag.</I> p919, no. 414.
	</A>
From an unknown play.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note123" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref123
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">123</A>
Archytas of Tarentum was a statesman, Pythagorean philosopher, and mathematician. He was seven times


<A ID="p277x"></A>general and never defeated. He lived in the fourth century <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> and was a friend of Plato.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note124" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref124
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">124</A>
Probably Battus III of Cyrene is meant, under whom the constitution of the city was reformed about the middle of the sixth century <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note125" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref125
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">125</A>
Homer, <I>Il.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">IV</SPAN>.130.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note126" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref126
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">126</A>
Dionysius II of Syracuse; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Timoleon*.html#13.10
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><I>Life of Timoleon</I>, chap. xiii</A>, and
	<A HREF="
https://penelope.uchicago.edu/aelian/varhist6.xhtml#chap12
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Aelian, <I>Var. Hist.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">VI</SPAN>.12</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note127" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref127
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">127</A>
Plato, <I>Republic</I>, 398<SPAN CLASS="small">E</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note128" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref128
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">128</A>
Lamachus was an Athenian general who was killed in the battle at the Anapus near Syracuse in 414 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note129" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref129
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">129</A>
Phocion was a famous Athenian general in the fourth century <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> He was elected general <SPAN CLASS="whole">forty-five</SPAN> times. He was virtual ruler of Athens when Antipater was in power, but in 318 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> was tried and executed by the Athenians.


<A ID="p283x"></A>Soon after that a public burial and a statue were decreed for him. The story told here is found also in the <I>Moralia</I>,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/De_vitioso_pudore*.html#T533a
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
p533<SPAN CLASS="small">A</SPAN></A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note130" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref130
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">130</A>
About six pints.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note131" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref131
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">131</A>
About a bushel and a half.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note132" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref132
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">132</A>
<I>Cf.</I> Pollux,
	<A HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/onomasticon01polluoft#page/n267/mode/2up
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN>.87</A>,
	<A HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/onomasticon01polluoft#page/n581/mode/2up
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">IX</SPAN>.84</A>, but, as Bernardakis suggests, Plutarch may have added the word for "more desirable," in which case there is here no real quotation.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note133" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref133
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">133</A>
	<A HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/tragicorumgraeco00naucuoft#page/919/mode/2up
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Nauck, <I>Trag. Graec. Frag.</I> p919, no. 415.
	</A>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note134" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref134
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">134</A>
	<A HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/tragicorumgraeco00naucuoft#page/853/mode/2up
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Nauck, <I>Trag. Graec. Frag.</I> p853, no. 75</A>;
	<A HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/comicorumatticor03kockuoft#page/612/mode/2up
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Kock, <I>Com. Att. Frag.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN> p612, no. 1229</A>.
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/De_capienda*.html#T88e
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Plutarch, <I>Moralia</I>, 88<SPAN CLASS="small">E</SPAN></A>,


<A ID="p287x"></A>uses the same simile, and this line is quoted as a proverb by Aristotle, <I>Meteor.</I> 364 <SPAN CLASS="small">B</SPAN>13.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note135" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref135
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">135</A>
This refers to the doctrine held by the Epicurean and Sceptic Schools of philosophy that the perfect state is that of complete tranquillity.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note136" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref136
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">136</A>
Theramenes was prominent in the oligarchy at Athens in 411 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>, but later turned against his former associates. In 404 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> he was elected one of the "Thirty Tyrants," but


<A ID="p291x"></A>tried to restrain his colleagues and was put to death by them. He was nicknamed Cothurnus because the buskin could be worn on either foot, as he was a member of each party in turn (<I>cf.</I> "turncoat"). Aristotle, <I>Constitution of Athens</I>, 28.5, praises him as a patriot.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note137" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref137
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">137</A>
For the phrase <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
https://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Thuc.+2.36
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Thucydides,WIDTH,220)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Thucydides, <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.36.4</A>.<A CLASS="correction"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(CarelessLoeb70+'II.364</SPAN>',WIDTH,216)"
onMouseOut="nd();">º</A>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note138" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Praecepta_gerendae_reipublicae*.html#ref138
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">138</A>
Hesiod, <I>Works and Days</I>, 233.



